## Memory Hierarchy Interpretation

The experiment naturally traverses the memory hierarchy:

```text
32–128
↓
L1 Cache Friendly

256–512
↓
L2/L3 Transition

1024–2048
↓
L3 Dominated

4096
↓
Main Memory Dominated
```

---

## Key Insight

This experiment demonstrates that matrix multiplication performance is not governed solely by arithmetic complexity.

Instead, execution time is strongly influenced by where the working set resides:

```text
Registers
↓
L1 Cache
↓
L2 Cache
↓
L3 Cache
↓
Main Memory
```

As matrices grow, data gradually falls out of faster storage levels.

Eventually, the processor spends most of its time moving data rather than performing multiplication.

---

## Final Conclusion

The IKJ implementation successfully exploits cache locality for small and medium matrix sizes.

However, as matrix dimensions increase:

* cache effectiveness decreases,
* memory traffic increases,
* and execution time converges toward the theoretical cubic growth of matrix multiplication.

This experiment provides a practical demonstration of the interaction between algorithmic complexity and the CPU memory hierarchy.
